         <c id="ref25" level="file">
            <did>
               <unittitle>Platt, Captain Epenetus</unittitle>
            </did>
            <c id="ref26" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>DS, "confession" to the New Milford Committee of Inspection of "those words and actions which the Committee and others have just reason to complain of" and making retraction so that "we may no longer be Estemed Enimys to our country." With 25 additional signatures. ([2] p. on one leaf)</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1775 November 27</unitdate>
                  <container altrender="archive half legal"
                             containerid="39002042257346"
                             id="d1e565"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="d1e567" localtype="folder" parent="d1e565">13</container>
               </did>
               <odd id="aspace_dfe8ce592881f8ab2f01792fa2d220eb">
                  <head>General</head>
                  <p>
                     <emph render="italic">Historical note:</emph> Epenetus Platt was appointed captain of the first company or trainband in the town of New Milford in May 1773. In February 1781 he was imprisoned in New Gate gaol for a treasonable writing and freed in May of that year on payment of a fine and bond "for the future peacable and obedient behavior…during the present war with Great Britain."(**) In May 1786 he was released from this conviction.(***)</p>
                  <p>(**) <emph render="italic">The Public Records of the State of Connecticut from May 1780 to October 1781</emph>…Charles J. Hoadly, compiler. Hartford, 1922. v.3, p. 433.</p>
                  <p>(***) <emph render="italic">Ibid</emph>., v.6, p. 185.</p>
               </odd>
            </c>
         </c>
